This paper deals with distributed computing and fault-tolerant state machine replication, which are typical topics in the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper also discusses Byzantine Agreement, which is a well-known problem in cryptography and security, making the Cryptography and Security (cs.CR) sub-category another likely candidate. The paper's focus on communication complexity and expected running time suggests that it could also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category or the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. Finally, the paper's use of probabilistic analysis and optimization techniques could make it relevant to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
